Conservation laws, symmetries, and line soliton
solutions of generalized KP and Boussinesq
equations with p𝑝p-power nonlinearities
in two dimensions

S.C. Anco1, M.L. Gandarias2, E. Recio2
1Brock University, St Catharines Canada
2Cadiz University, Cadiz Spain
Abstract

Nonlinear generalizations of integrable equations in one dimension, such as the KdV and Boussinesq equations with p𝑝p-power nonlinearities, arise in many physical applications and are interesting in analysis due to critical behaviour. This paper studies analogous nonlinear p𝑝p-power generalizations of the integrable KP equation and the Boussinesq equation in two dimensions. Several results are obtained. First, for all p≠0𝑝0p\neq 0, a Hamiltonian formulation of both generalized equations is given. Second, all Lie symmetries are derived, including any that exist for special powers p≠0𝑝0p\neq 0. Third, Noether’s theorem is applied to obtain the conservation laws arising from the Lie symmetries that are variational. Finally, explicit line soliton solutions are derived for all powers p>0𝑝0p>0, and some of their properties are discussed.

1 Introduction

The Kadomtsev-Petviashvili (KP) equation

are integrable systems in 2+1212+1 dimensions. These equations arise in important physical applications, most notably as models for shallow water waves [1], ion acoustic waves [13], and magnetic excitations in thin films [25], and they possess line soliton and lump solutions [22, 23, 16, 12, 14]. Both equations have a rich mathematical structure. In particular, their dimensional reductions yield many physically relevant integrable systems in 1+1111+1 dimensions.

Nonlinear generalizations of 1+1111+1 dimensional integrable systems with p𝑝p-power nonlinearities have been extensively studied. The best known example is the generalized Korteweg-de Vries (KdV) equation ut+up​u+ux​x​x=0subscript𝑢𝑡superscript𝑢𝑝𝑢subscript𝑢𝑥𝑥𝑥0u_{t}+u^{p}u+u_{xxx}=0, with p≠0𝑝0p\neq 0, which becomes the ordinary KdV equation when p=1𝑝1p=1 and the modified KdV equation when p=2𝑝2p=2. The KdV equation is a model of uni-directional shallow water waves, and the modified KdV equation models uni-directional ion acoustic waves. This stability extends to the critical case p=4𝑝4p=4 for solitary waves of sufficiently small energy.

There has been much less study of p𝑝p-power generalizations of the KP and modified KP equations themselves. In particular, the generalized KP (gKP) equation

(ut+α​up​ux+ux​x​x)x+β​uy​y=0,p≠0formulae-sequencesubscriptsubscript𝑢𝑡𝛼superscript𝑢𝑝subscript𝑢𝑥subscript𝑢𝑥𝑥𝑥𝑥𝛽subscript𝑢𝑦𝑦0𝑝0(u_{t}+\alpha u^{p}u_{x}+u_{xxx})_{x}+\beta u_{yy}=0,\quad p\neq 0 (3)

is a natural 2+1212+1 dimensional analog of the gKdV equation. An interesting variant is given by

ut​t=ux​x+α​(up+1)x​x+γ​ux​x​x​x+β​uy​y,p≠0formulae-sequencesubscript𝑢𝑡𝑡subscript𝑢𝑥𝑥𝛼subscriptsuperscript𝑢𝑝1𝑥𝑥𝛾subscript𝑢𝑥𝑥𝑥𝑥𝛽subscript𝑢𝑦𝑦𝑝0u_{tt}=u_{xx}+\alpha(u^{p+1})_{xx}+\gamma u_{xxxx}+\beta u_{yy},\quad p\neq 0 (4)

which is a 2+1212+1 dimensional generalized Boussinesq (2D gB) equation. Its reduction to 1+1111+1 dimensions gives a p𝑝p-power generalization of the ordinary Boussinesq equation

ut​t=ux​x+α​(u2)x​x+γ​ux​x​x​x.subscript𝑢𝑡𝑡subscript𝑢𝑥𝑥𝛼subscriptsuperscript𝑢2𝑥𝑥𝛾subscript𝑢𝑥𝑥𝑥𝑥u_{tt}=u_{xx}+\alpha(u^{2})_{xx}+\gamma u_{xxxx}. (5)

This equation is an integrable system which can be obtained by dimensional reduction of the KP equation, and it is a physically relevant model of bi-directional shallow water waves. One very interesting feature of the Boussinesq equation when γ<0𝛾0\gamma<0 is that its solitary wave solutions have an instability which can lead to formation of a singularity in a finite time [9, 11]. This behaviour is in contrast to the typical stability property of solitons in integrable systems.

The purpose of the present paper is to determine the conservation laws, symmetries, and line soliton solutions admitted by the gKP equation (3) and the 2D gB equation (4) in 2+1212+1 dimensions, for all nonlinearity powers p>0𝑝0p>0.

First, in section 2, both the gKP and 2D gB equations for arbitrary p≠0𝑝0p\neq 0 are formulated as Hamiltonian systems by the introduction of potentials. Next, all Lie point symmetries are obtained in section 3, and the class of variational point symmetries is found. Through Noether’s theorem in the Hamiltonian setting, the corresponding conservation laws are derived in section 4. These results include any point symmetries and any Noether conservation laws that arise for special powers p≠0𝑝0p\neq 0.

In section 5, line solitons u=U​(x+μ​y−ν​t)𝑢𝑈𝑥𝜇𝑦𝜈𝑡u=U(x+\mu y-\nu t) are considered for both the gKP and 2D gB equations for all p>0𝑝0p>0, where the parameters μ𝜇\mu and ν𝜈\nu determine the direction and the speed of the line soliton. The resulting fourth-order nonlinear differential equations for U𝑈U are directly reduced to first-order separable differential equations by use of the conservation laws obtained for the gKP and 2D gB equations. These separable differential equations are then integrated to get the explicit form of the line soliton solutions for all p>0𝑝0p>0, with μ𝜇\mu and c𝑐c being arbitrary apart from satisfying a kinematic inequality. Some properties of these solutions are discussed.

Finally, a few concluding remarks are made in section 6.

A few conservation laws of the gKP equation (3) in the case p=2𝑝2p=2 and the 2D gB equation (4) in the case p=2𝑝2p=2 have been found previously in Refs.[18, 21]. Some solutions of the gKP equation in three dimensions, without any discussion of their properties, are obtained in Ref.[2] A general treatment of symmetries, conservation laws, and their applications to differential equations can be found in Refs.[20, 7].

3 Symmetries

Symmetries are a basic structure of nonlinear evolution equations. They yield transformation groups under which the set of solutions of a given evolution equation is mapped into itself, and thus they can be used to find group-invariant solutions.

We will first consider point symmetries (x,y,t,v)→(x~,y~,t~,v~)→𝑥𝑦𝑡𝑣~𝑥~𝑦~𝑡~𝑣(x,y,t,v)\to(\tilde{x},\tilde{y},\tilde{t},\tilde{v}), where x~,y~,t~,v~~𝑥~𝑦~𝑡~𝑣\tilde{x},\tilde{y},\tilde{t},\tilde{v} are functions of x,y,t,v𝑥𝑦𝑡𝑣x,y,t,v. 3.1 Variational symmetries

We next determine which of the symmetries in Theorems 3.1 and 3.2 are variational.

Recall, an infinitesimal symmetry X^=P​∂v^X𝑃subscript𝑣\mathrm{\hat{X}}=P\partial_{v} is a variational symmetry if it leaves invariant any given Lagrangian L𝐿L up to a total divergence,

X^​L=Dt​Ψt+Dx​Ψx+Dy​Ψy^X𝐿subscript𝐷𝑡superscriptΨ𝑡subscript𝐷𝑥superscriptΨ𝑥subscript𝐷𝑦superscriptΨ𝑦\mathrm{\hat{X}}L=D_{t}\Psi^{t}+D_{x}\Psi^{x}+D_{y}\Psi^{y} (49)

where Ψt,Ψx,ΨysuperscriptΨ𝑡superscriptΨ𝑥superscriptΨ𝑦\Psi^{t},\Psi^{x},\Psi^{y} are functions of t𝑡t, x𝑥x, y𝑦y, v𝑣v, and derivatives of v𝑣v. Typically, this invariance condition is checked by first computing X^​L^X𝐿\mathrm{\hat{X}}L and then attempting to use integration by parts to bring this expression into the form of a total divergence. A much more efficient method can be used, which is based on the Euler operator (i.e. the variational derivative)

4 Conservation laws

Conservation laws are of basic importance for nonlinear evolution equations because, for all solutions, they provide physical, conserved quantities as well as conserved norms

For the gKP and 2D gB equations (9) and (14), a local conservation law is a continuity equation

Dt​T+Dx​X+Dy​Y=0subscript𝐷𝑡𝑇subscript𝐷𝑥𝑋subscript𝐷𝑦𝑌0D_{t}T+D_{x}X+D_{y}Y=0 (54)

holding for all solutions v​(x,y,t)𝑣𝑥𝑦𝑡v(x,y,t) of these respective equations, where T𝑇T is the conserved density, and (X,Y)𝑋𝑌(X,Y) is the spatial flux, which are functions of t𝑡t, x𝑥x, y𝑦y, v𝑣v, and derivatives of v𝑣v. When solutions v​(x,y,t)𝑣𝑥𝑦𝑡v(x,y,t) are considered in a given spatial domain Ω⊆ℝ2Ωsuperscriptℝ2\Omega\subseteq{\mathbb{R}}^{2}, every conservation law yields a corresponding conserved integral

𝒞​[v]=∫ΩT​𝑑x​𝑑y𝒞delimited-[]𝑣subscriptΩ𝑇differential-d𝑥differential-d𝑦\mathcal{C}[v]=\int_{\Omega}T\,dx\,dy (55)

satisfying the global balance equation

dd​t​𝒞​[v]=−∫∂Ω(X,Y)⋅𝐧^​𝑑s𝑑𝑑𝑡𝒞delimited-[]𝑣subscriptΩ⋅𝑋𝑌^𝐧differential-d𝑠\frac{d}{dt}\mathcal{C}[v]=-\int_{\partial\Omega}(X,Y)\cdot\hat{\mathbf{n}}\,ds (56)

where 𝐧^^𝐧\hat{\mathbf{n}} is the unit outward normal vector of the domain boundary curve ∂ΩΩ\partial\Omega, and where d​s𝑑𝑠ds is the arclength on this curve. This global equation (56) has the physical meaning that the rate of change of the quantity (55) on the spatial domain is balanced by the net outward flux through the boundary of the domain.

A conservation law is locally trivial if, for all solutions v​(x,y,t)𝑣𝑥𝑦𝑡v(x,y,t) in ΩΩ\Omega, the conserved density T𝑇T reduces to a spatial divergence Dx​Ψx+Dy​Ψysubscript𝐷𝑥superscriptΨ𝑥subscript𝐷𝑦superscriptΨ𝑦D_{x}\Psi^{x}+D_{y}\Psi^{y} and the spatial flux (X,Y)𝑋𝑌(X,Y) reduces to a time derivative −Dt​(Ψx,Ψy)subscript𝐷𝑡superscriptΨ𝑥superscriptΨ𝑦-D_{t}(\Psi^{x},\Psi^{y}), since then the global balance equation (56) becomes an identity. Likewise, two conservation laws are locally equivalent if they differ by a locally trivial conservation law, for all solutions v​(x,y,t)𝑣𝑥𝑦𝑡v(x,y,t) in ΩΩ\Omega. We will be interested only in locally non-trivial conservation laws.

Any non-trivial conservation law (54) can be expressed in an equivalent characteristic form [20, 7, 3] which is given by a divergence identity holding off of the space of solutions v​(x,y,t)𝑣𝑥𝑦𝑡v(x,y,t). For the gKP and 2D gB equations, conservation laws have the respective characteristic forms

and

Consequently, note that the characteristic equation of a conservation law is locally equivalent to the conservation law itself.

Since the gKP equation and the 2D gB equation each possess a Lagrangian formulation, Noether’s theorem [20, 7] shows that for both equations a one-to-one correspondence holds between locally non-trivial conservation laws (up to equivalence) and variational symmetries. Specifically, this correspondence can stated simply as

Q=P𝑄𝑃Q=P (59)

where Q𝑄Q is a conservation law multiplier and P𝑃P is a variational symmetry characteristic. The conserved density T~~𝑇\tilde{T} and the spatial flux (X~,Y~)~𝑋~𝑌(\tilde{X},\tilde{Y}) corresponding to a given variational symmetry characteristic P𝑃P can be obtained straightforwardly by several methods [26, 7, 3], starting from the characteristic equations (57) and (58).

5 Line soliton solutions

A line soliton is a solitary travelling wave

A more geometrical form for a line soliton is given by writing x+μ​y=(x,y)⋅𝐤𝑥𝜇𝑦⋅𝑥𝑦𝐤x+\mu y=(x,y)\cdot{\mathbf{k}} with 𝐤=(1,μ)𝐤1𝜇{\mathbf{k}}=(1,\mu) being a constant vector in the (x,y)𝑥𝑦(x,y)-plane. The travelling wave variable can then be expressed as

where the unit vector

𝐤^=(cos⁡θ,sin⁡θ),tan⁡θ=μformulae-sequence^𝐤𝜃𝜃𝜃𝜇\hat{\mathbf{k}}=(\cos\theta,\sin\theta),\quad\tan\theta=\mu (93)

Hence when the direction of motion is within an angle of π/4𝜋4\pi/4 with respect to the x𝑥x-axis in the case σ2=−1superscript𝜎21\sigma^{2}=-1, there is a minimum speed |c|>(1−μ2)/(1+μ2)>0𝑐1superscript𝜇21superscript𝜇20|c|>\sqrt{(1-\mu^{2})/(1+\mu^{2})}>0.

Second, in the “−-” case of the 2D gB equation, the line soliton parameters μ𝜇\mu and ν𝜈\nu need to obey the opposite kinematic condition

ν2<sgn​(σ2)​μ2+1.superscript𝜈2sgnsuperscript𝜎2superscript𝜇21\nu^{2}<{\rm sgn}(\sigma^{2})\mu^{2}+1. (112)

Consequently, in the case σ2=1superscript𝜎21\sigma^{2}=1, there is a maximum speed |c|<1𝑐1|c|<1. In the case σ2=−1superscript𝜎21\sigma^{2}=-1, the direction of motion is confined to within an angle of π/4𝜋4\pi/4 with respect to the x𝑥x-axis, with the speed obeying |c|<(1−μ2)/(1+μ2)𝑐1superscript𝜇21superscript𝜇2|c|<\sqrt{(1-\mu^{2})/(1+\mu^{2})}. These kinematical properties are independent of the nonlinearity power.

6 Concluding remarks

For the generalized KP equation (3) and the 2D generalized Boussinesq equation (4) with p𝑝p-power nonlinearities, we have derived all conservation laws that arise from variational point symmetries and used them to obtain the general line soliton solutions of these two equations for all powers p>0𝑝0p>0. We have also discussed some basic kinematical properties of the line solitons.

Our results can be further used as a starting point to investigate the stability of the line soliton solutions for the gKP equation. It is known that [13, 19] the line solitons of the KP equation (p=1𝑝1p=1) are stable in the case σ2=1superscript𝜎21\sigma^{2}=1 and unstable in the opposite case σ2=−1superscript𝜎21\sigma^{2}=-1. An interesting question is to determine the stability of the line solitons for higher powers p≥2𝑝2p\geq 2. Compared to the KdV equation, in two dimensions the critical power for the conserved mass is p=43𝑝43p=\tfrac{4}{3}, while the critical power for the conserved energy is p=4𝑝4p=4.

In addition to line soliton solutions, the KP equation possesses lump solutions, which are rational functions and involve several parameters. No lump solutions are known for the modified KP equation, and an interesting question is to see if a similar result will hold for the gKP equation for all p>1𝑝1p>1.

Stability of line solitons and existence of lump solutions can be investigated similarly for the 2D gB equation.
